```python
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Simulating the loading of data
data = {
    'Country': ['China', 'India', 'United States', 'Indonesia', 'Pakistan', 'Brazil', 'Nigeria', 'Bangladesh', 'Russia', 'Mexico'],
    'Population': [1444216107, 1393409038, 331893745, 273523621, 225199937, 213993437, 206139587, 166303498, 143993641, 130262216]
}

# Creating a DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Plotting the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(df['Country'], df['Population'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Population')
plt.title('Population Distribution by Country')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()
```

This script creates a bar chart showing the population distribution of the selected countries. 

If you want to visualize this with an actual dataset, you would need to download the data from the provided link, load it into a DataFrame using `pd.read_csv()`, and then follow similar steps to create the chart.
